可。她至少有1个女儿。"},"hr":{"about 1450–":"oko 1450.–preminula","1476–Female":"1476–preminula","1450–Female":"1450–preminula","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"oko 1450.","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"cs":{"about 1450–":"okolo 1450–Zesnulá","1476–Female":"1476–Zesnulá","1450–Female":"1450–Zesnulá","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"okolo 1450","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1450–":"omkring 1450–Afdød","1476–Female":"1476–Afdød","1450–Female":"1450–Afdød","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"omkring 1450","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1450–":"circa 1450–Overleden","1476–Female":"1476–Overleden","1450–Female":"1450–Overleden","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"circa 1450","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1450–":"about 1450–Deceased","1476–Female":"1476–Deceased","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"about 1450","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Parker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>parker</i> ‘park-keeper’ (Old French <i>parquier</i>, <i>parchier</i>), an officer employed to look after deer and other game in a hunting park (see   Park   1). This surname is also very common among African Americans. It has also been recorded since medieval times in Ireland.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish names."],"variants":[{"name":"Parkman","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>park</i> ‘enclosure, game preserve, park’ (Old French <i>parc</i>) + <i>man</i>, sometimes for one living at or near such a place but probably more often denoting someone employed to look after after deer and other game in a hunting park; compare   Parker  .","occupational name denoting the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of someone called <i>Park</i> (see   Park   2)."]},{"name":"Parkerson","meanings":["English: from the occupational name   Parker   + patronymic <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Parkey","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): dialect pronunciation of   Parker  . <i>Parker</i> has a long history in Macclesfield, Manchester, and Bridgnorth."]},{"name":"Park","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Sang, Sung, Yong, Jung, Jong, Chan, Jae, Jin, Kwang, Kyung, Myung, Chong, Chang, Chung, Byung, Min, Moon, Chul, Hae, Jeong, Dae, Seong, Myong.","English and Scottish: from Middle English and Older Scots <i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705201,"age":99,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":108,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Parker was born about 1450, in Norfolk, England. She had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1450–":"umbes 1450–Surnud","1476–Female":"1476–Surnud","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1450–":"noin 1450–Kuollut","1476–Female":"1476–Kuollut","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","about 1450":"noin 1450","Norfolk, Engl